# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: boundary-value-problems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] In the study of differential equations, a **boundary-value problem** is a differential equation subjected to constraints called **boundary conditions**.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] A solution to a boundary value problem is a solution to the differential equation which also satisfies the boundary conditions.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] Boundary value problems arise in several branches of physics as any physical differential equation will have them.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] Problems involving the wave equation, such as the determination of normal modes, are often stated as boundary value problems.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] A large class of important boundary value problems are the Sturm–Liouville problems.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] The analysis of these problems, in the linear case, involves the eigenfunctions of a differential operator.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] To be useful in applications, a boundary value problem should be well posed.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] This means that given the input to the problem there exists a unique solution, which depends continuously on the input.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] Much theoretical work in the field of partial differential equations is devoted to proving that boundary value problems arising from scientific and engineering applications are in fact well-posed.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] Among the earliest boundary value problems to be studied is the Dirichlet problem, of finding the harmonic functions (solutions to Laplace's equation); the solution was given by the Dirichlet's principle.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] Boundary value problems are similar to initial value problems.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] A **boundary value** is a data value that corresponds to a minimum or maximum input, internal, or output value specified for a system or component.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] For example, if the independent variable is time over the domain [0,1], a boundary value problem would specify values for $y(t)$ at both $t=0$ and $t=1$ , whereas an initial value problem would specify a value of $y(t)$ and $y'(t)$ at time $t=0$ .
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] Finding the temperature at all points of an iron bar with one end kept at absolute zero and the other end at the freezing point of water would be a boundary value problem.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] If the problem is dependent on both space and time, one could specify the value of the problem at a given point for all time or at a given time for all space.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] The 3 standard classes of conditions are Dirichlet, Neumann and Cauchy or Robin, with also mixed, boundary as infinity.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] Summary of boundary conditions for the unknown function, y , constants $c_{0}$ and $c_{1}$ specified by the boundary conditions, and known scalar functions f and g specified by the boundary conditions.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] A type 1 boundary condition, Dirichlet boundary condition, specifies the value of the function itself.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] For example, if one end of an iron rod is held at absolute zero, then the value of the problem would be known at that point in space.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] A type 2 boundary condition, Neumann boundary condition, specifies the value of the normal derivative of the function.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] For example, if there is a heater at one end of an iron rod, then energy would be added at a constant rate but the actual temperature would not be known.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] A type 3 boundary condition is the Robin condition.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] If the boundary has the form of a curve or surface that gives a value to the normal derivative and the variable itself then it is a Cauchy boundary condition.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] A type 0 boundary condition has no physical boundary.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] Aside from the boundary condition, boundary value problems are also classified according to the type of differential operator involved.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] For an elliptic operator, one discusses elliptic boundary value problems.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] For a hyperbolic operator, one discusses hyperbolic boundary value problems.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] These categories are further subdivided into linear and various nonlinear types.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] In electrostatics, a common problem is to find a function which describes the electric potential of a given region.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] If the region does not contain charge, the potential must be a solution to Laplace's equation (a so-called harmonic function).
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] The boundary conditions in this case are the Interface conditions for electromagnetic fields.
[src:boundary-value-problems/boundary-value-problem] If there is no current density in the region, it is also possible to define a magnetic scalar potential using a similar procedure.
[src:boundary-value-problems/cauchy-boundary-condition] In mathematics, a **Cauchy** (French: [koʃi]) **boundary condition** augments an ordinary differential equation or a partial differential equation with conditions that the solution must satisfy on the boundary; ideally so as to ensure that a unique solution exists.
[src:boundary-value-problems/cauchy-boundary-condition] A Cauchy boundary condition specifies both the function value and normal derivative on the boundary of the domain.
[src:boundary-value-problems/cauchy-boundary-condition] This corresponds to imposing both a Dirichlet and a Neumann boundary condition.
[src:boundary-value-problems/cauchy-boundary-condition] It is named after the prolific 19th-century French mathematical analyst Augustin-Louis Cauchy.
[src:boundary-value-problems/cauchy-boundary-condition] Since the parameter s is usually time, Cauchy conditions can also be called *initial value conditions* or *initial value data* or simply *Cauchy data*.
[src:boundary-value-problems/cauchy-boundary-condition] An example of such a situation is Newton's laws of motion, where the acceleration $y''$ depends on position y , velocity $y'$ , and the time s ; here, Cauchy data corresponds to knowing the initial position and velocity.
[src:boundary-value-problems/cauchy-boundary-condition] For partial differential equations, Cauchy boundary conditions specify both the function and the normal derivative on the boundary.
[src:boundary-value-problems/cauchy-boundary-condition] where $\psi (x,y)$ is the unknown solution, $\psi _{x}$ denotes derivative of $\psi$ with respect to x etc.
[src:boundary-value-problems/cauchy-boundary-condition] The functions $A,B,C,F$ specify the problem.
[src:boundary-value-problems/cauchy-boundary-condition] hold for all boundary points $(x,y)\in \partial \Omega$ .
[src:boundary-value-problems/cauchy-boundary-condition] Here $\mathbf {n} \cdot \nabla \psi$ is the derivative in the direction of the normal to the boundary.
[src:boundary-value-problems/cauchy-boundary-condition] The functions $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are the Cauchy data.
[src:boundary-value-problems/cauchy-boundary-condition] Notice the difference between a Cauchy boundary condition and a Robin boundary condition.
[src:boundary-value-problems/cauchy-boundary-condition] In the former, we specify both the function and the normal derivative.
[src:boundary-value-problems/cauchy-boundary-condition] In the latter, we specify a weighted average of the two.
[src:boundary-value-problems/cauchy-boundary-condition] We would like boundary conditions to ensure that exactly one (unique) solution exists, but for second-order partial differential equations, it is not as simple to guarantee existence and uniqueness as it is for ordinary differential equations.
[src:boundary-value-problems/cauchy-boundary-condition] Cauchy data are most immediately relevant for hyperbolic problems (for example, the wave equation) on open domains (for example, the half plane).
[src:boundary-value-problems/dirichlet-boundary-condition] In mathematics, the **Dirichlet** **boundary condition** is imposed on an ordinary or partial differential equation, such that the values that the solution takes along the boundary of the domain are fixed.
[src:boundary-value-problems/dirichlet-boundary-condition] The question of finding solutions to such equations is known as the Dirichlet problem.
[src:boundary-value-problems/dirichlet-boundary-condition] In the sciences and engineering, a Dirichlet boundary condition may also be referred to as a **fixed boundary condition** or **boundary condition of the first type**.
[src:boundary-value-problems/dirichlet-boundary-condition] It is named after Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet (1805–1859).
[src:boundary-value-problems/dirichlet-boundary-condition] In finite-element analysis, the *essential* or Dirichlet boundary condition is defined by weighted-integral form of a differential equation.
[src:boundary-value-problems/dirichlet-boundary-condition] The dependent unknown *u in the same form as the weight function w* appearing in the boundary expression is termed a *primary variable*, and its specification constitutes the *essential* or Dirichlet boundary condition.
[src:boundary-value-problems/dirichlet-boundary-condition] For an ordinary differential equation, for instance, $y''+y=0,$ the Dirichlet boundary conditions on the interval [*a*,*b*] take the form $y(a)=\alpha ,\quad y(b)=\beta ,$ where α and β are given numbers.
[src:boundary-value-problems/dirichlet-boundary-condition] For a partial differential equation, for example, $\nabla ^{2}y+y=0,$ where $\nabla ^{2}$ denotes the Laplace operator, the Dirichlet boundary conditions on a domain Ω ⊂ **R***n* take the form $y(x)=f(x)\quad \forall x\in \partial \Omega ,$ where f is a known function defined on the boundary ∂Ω.
[src:boundary-value-problems/dirichlet-boundary-condition] Many other boundary conditions are possible, including the Cauchy boundary condition and the mixed boundary condition.
[src:boundary-value-problems/dirichlet-boundary-condition] The latter is a combination of the Dirichlet and Neumann conditions.
[src:boundary-value-problems/mixed-boundary-condition] In mathematics, a **mixed boundary condition** for a partial differential equation defines a boundary value problem in which the solution of the given equation is required to satisfy different boundary conditions on disjoint parts of the boundary of the domain where the condition is stated.
[src:boundary-value-problems/mixed-boundary-condition] Precisely, in a mixed boundary value problem, the solution is required to satisfy a Dirichlet or a Neumann boundary condition in a mutually exclusive way on disjoint parts of the boundary.
[src:boundary-value-problems/mixed-boundary-condition] where *u* 0 and *g* are given functions defined on those portions of the boundary.
[src:boundary-value-problems/mixed-boundary-condition] The mixed boundary condition differs from the Robin boundary condition in that the latter requires a linear combination, possibly with pointwise variable coefficients, of the Dirichlet and the Neumann boundary value conditions to be satisfied on the whole boundary of a given domain.
[src:boundary-value-problems/mixed-boundary-condition] The first boundary value problem satisfying a mixed boundary condition was solved by Stanisław Zaremba for the Laplace equation: according to himself, it was Wilhelm Wirtinger who suggested him to study this problem.
[src:boundary-value-problems/neumann-boundary-condition] In mathematics, the **Neumann** (or **second-type**) **boundary condition** is a type of boundary condition, named after Carl Neumann.
[src:boundary-value-problems/neumann-boundary-condition] When imposed on an ordinary or a partial differential equation, the condition specifies the values of the derivative applied at the boundary of the domain.
[src:boundary-value-problems/neumann-boundary-condition] where **n** denotes the (typically exterior) normal to the boundary ∂Ω, and f is a given scalar function.
[src:boundary-value-problems/neumann-boundary-condition] where ∇*y*(**x**) represents the gradient vector of *y*(**x**), **n̂** is the unit normal, and ⋅ represents the inner product operator.
[src:boundary-value-problems/neumann-boundary-condition] It becomes clear that the boundary must be sufficiently smooth such that the normal derivative can exist, since, for example, at corner points on the boundary the normal vector is not well defined.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] Poisson's equation is $\Delta \varphi =f,$ where $\Delta$ is the Laplace operator, and f and $\varphi$ are real or complex-valued functions on a manifold.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] Usually, f is given, and $\varphi$ is sought.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] When $f=0$ identically, we obtain Laplace's equation.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] Poisson's equation may be solved using a Green's function: $\varphi (\mathbf {r} )=-\iiint {\frac {f(\mathbf {r} ')}{4\pi |\mathbf {r} -\mathbf {r} '|}}\,\mathrm {d} ^{3}r',$ where the integral is over all of space.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] Note here r is where we observe the field, where we are solving for.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] And integrating $r'$ is equivalent to integrating all the "sources".
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] In a sense that we integrate all the effects of sources at $r'$ to get what's seen at r (with the addition of point spread of source).
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] A general exposition of the Green's function for Poisson's equation is given in the article on the screened Poisson equation.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] There are various methods for numerical solution, such as the relaxation method, an iterative algorithm.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] In the case of a gravitational field **g** due to an attracting massive object of density *ρ*, Gauss's law for gravity in differential form can be used to obtain the corresponding Poisson equation for gravity.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] If the mass density is zero, Poisson's equation reduces to Laplace's equation.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] The corresponding Green's function can be used to calculate the potential at distance r from a central point mass m (i.e., the fundamental solution).
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] In three dimensions the potential is $\phi (r)={\frac {-Gm}{r}},$ which is equivalent to Newton's law of universal gravitation.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] Many problems in electrostatics are governed by the Poisson equation, which relates the electric potential φ to the free charge density $\rho _{f}$ , such as those found in conductors.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] The mathematical details of Poisson's equation, commonly expressed in SI units (as opposed to Gaussian units), describe how the distribution of free charges generates the electrostatic potential in a given region.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] Assuming the medium is linear, isotropic, and homogeneous (see polarization density), we have the constitutive equation $\mathbf {D} =\varepsilon \mathbf {E} ,$ where ε is the permittivity of the medium, and **E** is the electric field.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] Then, we have that $\nabla \times \mathbf {E} =0,$ where ∇× is the curl operator.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] This equation means that we can write the electric field as the gradient of a scalar function φ (called the electric potential), since the curl of any gradient is zero.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] Thus we can write $\mathbf {E} =-\nabla \varphi ,$ where the minus sign is introduced so that φ is identified as the electric potential energy per unit charge.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] The derivation of Poisson's equation under these circumstances is straightforward.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] Specifying the Poisson's equation for the potential requires knowing the charge density distribution.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] If the charge density is zero, then Laplace's equation results.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] If the charge density follows a Boltzmann distribution, then the Poisson–Boltzmann equation results.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] The Poisson–Boltzmann equation plays a role in the development of the Debye–Hückel theory of dilute electrolyte solutions.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] Using a Green's function, the potential at distance r from a central point charge Q (i.e., the fundamental solution) is $\varphi (r)={\frac {Q}{4\pi \varepsilon r}},$ which is Coulomb's law of electrostatics.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] The above discussion assumes that the magnetic field is not varying in time.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] The same Poisson equation arises even if it does vary in time, as long as the Coulomb gauge is used.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] In this more general class of cases, computing φ is no longer sufficient to calculate **E**, since **E** also depends on the magnetic vector potential **A**, which must be independently computed.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] See Maxwell's equation in potential formulation for more on φ and **A** in Maxwell's equations and how an appropriate Poisson's equation is obtained in this case.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] This solution can be checked explicitly by evaluating ∇2*φ*.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] Note that for r much greater than σ, ${\textstyle \operatorname {erf} (r/{\sqrt {2}}\sigma )}$ approaches unity, and the potential *φ*(*r*) approaches the point-charge potential, $\varphi \approx {\frac {1}{4\pi \varepsilon }}{\frac {Q}{r}},$ as one would expect.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] Furthermore, the error function approaches 1 extremely quickly as its argument increases; in practice, for *r* > 3.4*σ* the relative error is smaller than one part in a thousand.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] Surface reconstruction is an inverse problem.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] The goal is to digitally reconstruct a smooth surface based on a large number of points *pi* (a point cloud) where each point also carries an estimate of the local surface normal **n***i*.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] Poisson's equation can be utilized to solve this problem with a technique called Poisson surface reconstruction.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] The goal of this technique is to reconstruct an implicit function *f* whose value is zero at the points *pi* and whose gradient at the points *pi* equals the normal vectors **n***i*.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] The set of (*pi*, **n***i*) is thus modeled as a continuous vector field **V**.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] The implicit function *f* is found by integrating the vector field **V**.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] Since not every vector field is the gradient of a function, the problem may or may not have a solution: the necessary and sufficient condition for a smooth vector field **V** to be the gradient of a function *f* is that the curl of **V** must be identically zero.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] In case this condition is difficult to impose, it is still possible to perform a least-squares fit to minimize the difference between **V** and the gradient of *f*.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] In order to effectively apply Poisson's equation to the problem of surface reconstruction, it is necessary to find a good discretization of the vector field **V**.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] The basic approach is to bound the data with a finite-difference grid.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] For a function valued at the nodes of such a grid, its gradient can be represented as valued on staggered grids, i.e. on grids whose nodes lie in between the nodes of the original grid.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] It is convenient to define three staggered grids, each shifted in one and only one direction corresponding to the components of the normal data.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] On each staggered grid we perform trilinear interpolation on the set of points.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] The interpolation weights are then used to distribute the magnitude of the associated component of *ni* onto the nodes of the particular staggered grid cell containing *pi*.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] Kazhdan and coauthors give a more accurate method of discretization using an adaptive finite-difference grid, i.e. the cells of the grid are smaller (the grid is more finely divided) where there are more data points.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] They suggest implementing this technique with an adaptive octree.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] Thermal conduction is modelled via the Heat equation.
[src:boundary-value-problems/poisson-s-equation] where $\vartheta$ is the temperature, $\Phi$ is the heat source term and $\lambda$ is Thermal conductivity.
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] In mathematics, the **Robin boundary condition** (/ˈrɒbɪn/ *ROB-in*, French: [ʁɔbɛ̃]), or **third-type boundary condition**, is a type of boundary condition, named after Victor Gustave Robin (1855–1897).
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] It is used when solving partial differential equations and ordinary differential equations.
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] The Robin boundary condition specifies a linear combination of the value of a function and the value of its derivative at the boundary of a given domain.
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] It is a generalization of the Dirichlet boundary condition, which specifies only the function's value, and the Neumann boundary condition, which specifies only the function's derivative.
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] A common physical example is in heat transfer, where a surface might lose heat to the environment via convection.
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] The rate of heat flow (related to the derivative of temperature) would be proportional to the difference between the surface temperature (the value of the temperature function) and the ambient temperature.
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] Other equivalent names in use are **Fourier-type condition** and **radiation condition**.
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] Robin boundary conditions are a weighted combination of Dirichlet boundary conditions and Neumann boundary conditions.
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] This contrasts to mixed boundary conditions, which are boundary conditions of different types specified on different subsets of the boundary.
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] Robin boundary conditions are also called **impedance boundary conditions**, from their application in electromagnetic problems, or **convective boundary conditions**, from their application in heat transfer problems (Hahn, 2012).
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] for some non-zero constants *a* and *b* and a given function *g* defined on ∂Ω.
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] Here, *u* is the unknown solution defined on Ω and ⁠∂*u*/∂*n*⁠ denotes the normal derivative at the boundary.
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] More generally, *a* and *b* are allowed to be (given) functions, rather than constants.
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] Notice the change of sign in front of the term involving a derivative: that is because the normal to [0,1] at 0 points in the negative direction, while at 1 it points in the positive direction.
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] Robin boundary conditions are commonly used in solving Sturm–Liouville problems which appear in many contexts in science and engineering.
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] In addition, the Robin boundary condition is a general form of the **insulating boundary condition** for convection–diffusion equations.
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] where *D* is the diffusive constant, *u* is the convective velocity at the boundary and *c* is the concentration.
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] The second term is a result of Fick's law of diffusion.
[src:boundary-value-problems/robin-boundary-condition] A single Robin boundary condition on $\phi$ is also able to completely capture the geometrical capacitance in the 1D-like (parallel-plate capacitor or planar interface) case, such as when modelling a Stern layer.
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] In numerical analysis, the **shooting method** is a method for solving a boundary value problem by reducing it to an initial value problem.
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] It involves finding solutions to the initial value problem for different initial conditions until one finds the solution that also satisfies the boundary conditions of the boundary value problem.
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] In layman's terms, one "shoots" out trajectories in different directions from one boundary until one finds the trajectory that "hits" the other boundary condition.
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] The shooting method is the process of solving the initial value problem for many different values of a until one finds the solution $y(t;a)$ that satisfies the desired boundary conditions.
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] The solution(s) correspond to root(s) of $F(a)=y(t_{1};a)-y_{1}.$ To systematically vary the shooting parameter a and find the root, one can employ standard root-finding algorithms like the bisection method or Newton's method.
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] Roots of F and solutions to the boundary value problem are equivalent.
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] If a is a root of F , then $y(t;a)$ is a solution of the boundary value problem.
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] Conversely, if the boundary value problem has a solution $y(t)$ , it is also the unique solution $y(t;a)$ of the initial value problem where $a=y'(t_{0})$ , so a is a root of F .
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] The term "shooting method" has its origin in artillery.
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] Between each shot, the direction of the cannon is adjusted based on the previous shot, so every shot hits closer than the previous one.
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] The trajectory that "hits" the desired boundary value is the solution to the boundary value problem — hence the name "shooting method".
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] A boundary value problem is given as follows by Stoer and Bulirsch (Section 7.3.1).
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] Inspecting the plot of *F*, we see that there are roots near −8 and −36.
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] Some trajectories of *w*(*t*;*s*) are shown in the Figure 1.
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] Stoer and Bulirsch state that there are two solutions, which can be found by algebraic methods.
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] These correspond to the initial conditions *w*′(0) = −8 and *w*′(0) = −35.9 (approximately).
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] The shooting method can also be used to solve eigenvalue problems.
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] Count the roots of $\psi _{n}$ and refine the guess for the energy $E_{n}$ .
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] The energy-guessing can be done with the bisection method, and the process can be terminated when the energy difference is sufficiently small.
[src:boundary-value-problems/shooting-method] Then one can take any energy in the interval to be the correct energy.
